As a UW employee, you have a unique opportunity to change lives on our campuses, in our state and around the world. UW employees offer their boundless energy, creative problem solving skills and dedication to build stronger minds and a healthier world. UW faculty and staff also enjoy outstanding benefits, professional growth opportunities and unique resources in an environment noted for diversity, intellectual excitement, artistic pursuits and natural beauty. The UW Division of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (DAID) has an outstanding opportunity for a full-time data manager & analyst. This position will support the Chu Lab in clinical and laboratory data analysis for several large-scale studies of the epidemiology and transmission of SARS-CoV-2 and other respiratory pathogens in the Seattle area. This position will involve analysis of clinical and biospecimen data from community-based and clinical-based enrollment of individuals with respiratory illness, and analysis of these data to characterize the epidemiology of pathogens causing respiratory symptoms in a variety of diverse settings, the transmission of pathogens within households, and the clinical characteristics of individuals presenting with these pathogens. This is a collaborative project, and will involve interfacing with partnering stakeholders, clinicians, bioinformaticians, and a variety of study personnel, including trainees The Research Data Manager/Analyst will need to develop a deep understanding of each source-data structure, and have the intellectual dexterity to provide data management support (extraction, integration, validation) while collaborating with persons in a variety of fields: clinical informatics, data science, and epidemiology. Ideal candidates should have had solid experience with healthcare data, and excellent programming skills with SQL. We are seeking someone who is excited about the opportunity of working in a fast -paced environment, and who has resourcefulness, independent problem solving, excellent time management skills, attention to detail and the ability to negotiate and communicate priorities. DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES Data Investigation and Analysis (70%): Works with study PI(s), fellows, epidemiologists, bioinformaticians and other research staff to develop innovative solutions to abstract and integrate data in support of studies with large-scale data. Consults with faculty, fellows, coordinators and research scientists to interpret objectives and identify data needs. Generates complex database queries and ad hoc reports to uncover clinical trends and insights. Validates final data product through coordination with investigator. Investigates and identifies data idiosyncrasies and fluctuations and makes recommendations that support goals and objectives. Work independently to analyze study data using SAS, Stata or other software and prepare data for manuscripts. Methods Development and Study Planning (15%): Work closely with investigators to understand project goals, then independently develop the format of the data required to address the goals. Consider feasibility and appropriate data collection tools to develop analysis plans that will translate collected data into results. Work with investigators to explain the statistical processes and analysis plans developed and collaborate to refine methodologies as required. Utilize fundamental theories and develop them for application to specific project needs. This requires a strong comprehension of biostatistical analyses and an ability to develop innovative interpretations and applications of existing practices. Communication of Findings (10%): Summarize and interpret results of analyses for investigators and staff, incorporating appropriate inference and multiplicity adjustments. Prepare tabular, graphical, and statistical reports for scientific papers and grants, following the formatting requirements of the journals (eg high resolution graphics). Assist in writing papers and review them for correctness and completeness. Attend relevant study meetings including: Weekly data meetings, lab meetings, clinical meetings. Data Quality (5%): Work closely with Data Managers, Research Coordinators, and other staff to ensure the accuracy and consistency of data. Resolve data discrepancies and database issues through coordination with clinical team. Implement and maintain Data QC protocols for clinical trials and other research projects and collaborate with study partners on Data QA/QC workflow efficacy. Advise on case report form development and on dataset preparation. MINIMUM REQUIREMENTS Bachelor’s Degree in Bioinformatics, Statistics or related field and two years experience. Equivalent education/experience will substitute for all minimum qualifications except when there are legal requirements, such as a license/certification/registration. ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENTS Experience with R, SAS, Tableau or STATA. Strong troubleshooting skills in working with complex server configurations. Ability to adhere to institutional review board (IRB) regulations related to studies of human subjects. Ability to work well cross functionally, especially with technical teams. Demonstrated ability to maintain strict confidentiality of medical and surveillance records. DESIRED QUALIFICATIONS Advanced training in computer or data science, programming or informatics. Education in data science, health services research, health policy. Experience with Tableau and REDCap. Experience with Epic or other electronic health records systems. Experience in healthcare or medical data management, and/or biomedical informatics. POSITION PURPOSE The Collaborative Health Studies Coordinating Center (CHSCC) in the Department of Biostatistics is seeking a full-time data analyst/statistical programmer to join our collaborative research team. The CHSCC coordinates several large-scale cohort studies, primarily in cardiovascular epidemiology research, and enjoys an excellent reputation for design, coordination, and biostatistical analysis of such studies. This position is primarily with the Kidney Precision Medicine Project (KPMP) but will also support other studies active at the CHSCC. The person in this position will program visualizations of safety and quality control reports to share with study stakeholders. The statistician will also participate in epidemiologic research by actively engaging in data analysis for publication. This position requires a solid understanding of epidemiological principles and biostatistics. The person in this position will need to have a high degree of organizational ability, interest in working in varying subject areas, and strong analytic skills. The KPMP project is a high profile and important project for UW, and this COVID project contributes to public health in an important way during the pandemic. DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES 40% Program statistical reports for quality control and safety data. 30% Fulfill complex data requests for internal and external researchers. 20% Perform independent statistical analyses of data for publication in peer-reviewed journals. 10% participate in working group conference calls, work collaboratively with external investigators to co-author papers, and assist with sample size calculations. Equivalent education/experience will substitute for all minimum qualifications except when there are legal requirements, such as a license/certification/registration. Ability to program in at least one statistical programming language (i.e. R, Python) and familiarity with at least one major statistical analysis package (i.e. Stata, R).
